=========================================
AUTO + DECLTYPE (C++11)
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. Problem in Templates (Before C++11)
--------------------------------------
Earlier, return types of template functions were hard to define
when they depend on input parameter types.

Example:
T1 + T2 → result type is unknown

-----------------------------------------

2. Solution: auto + decltype
-----------------------------

C++11 allows:
✔ auto return type
✔ decltype to deduce expression type

-----------------------------------------

3. Syntax (IMPORTANT)
---------------------

template <typename T1, typename T2>
auto function(T1 a, T2 b) -> decltype(a + b)
{
    return a + b;
}

✔ auto → tells compiler return type is deduced
✔ decltype → gives type of expression (a + b)

-----------------------------------------

4. Example: Generic Addition
----------------------------

template<typename T1, typename T2>
auto add(T1 a, T2 b) -> decltype(a + b)
{
    return a + b;
}

int main()
{
    cout << add(1, 2) << endl;        // int
    cout << add(3.5, 2) << endl;      // double
}
-----------------------------------------

5. Why decltype is used?
------------------------

decltype(expression) gives exact type of expression:

Example:
int a = 5;
double b = 2.5;

decltype(a + b) → double

-----------------------------------------

6. Using decltype for Variable Declaration
------------------------------------------

We can also use decltype to declare variables
based on function return type.

Example:

decltype(add(1,2)) x;
decltype(add(3.4,1)) y;

-----------------------------------------

7. Example with type checking
-----------------------------

#include <iostream>
#include <typeinfo>
using namespace std;

template<typename T1, typename T2>
auto add(T1 a, T2 b) -> decltype(a + b)
{
    return a + b;
}

int main()
{
    decltype(add(1,2)) x;
    decltype(add(3.4,1)) y;

    cout << typeid(x).name() << endl;
    cout << typeid(y).name() << endl;
}

-----------------------------------------

8. Modern C++ (C++14 improvement)
----------------------------------

C++14 simplifies this:

template<typename T1, typename T2>
auto add(T1 a, T2 b)
{
    return a + b;
}

✔ No trailing return type needed

-----------------------------------------

9. Interview One-liner
-----------------------

auto + decltype allows writing generic functions where
return type is automatically deduced from expression type,
making templates more flexible and type-safe.

=========================================
QUICK REVISION
=========================================

1. auto → return type deduction
2. decltype → type of expression
3. Used in templates for dependent return types
4. Syntax: auto f() -> decltype(expr)
5. C++14 removes need for decltype in simple cases
